## 5) NON-NEGOTIABLE RULES

### 5.1 HUMAN-LED VISUALS (MANDATORY)

Every image must include a **human focal point**.

---

#### SUBJECT SELECTION (REQUIRED VARIATION)

For each output, assign a **unique human subject profile** before generating.

Each subject must differ across outputs in:
- archetype (role/lifestyle)
- gender presentation
- race/ethnicity
- styling (hair, outfit, vibe)
- overall energy

Do NOT reuse the same subject type consecutively.

Archetype pool (rotate through naturally):
- college student (male/female)
- young professional (male/female)
- business professional
- blue-collar worker
- creator / influencer type
- service worker (barista, retail, etc.)
- everyday casual person

Demographic variation rules:
- Vary gender presentation across outputs (male, female, neutral/androgynous when appropriate)
- Vary race/ethnicity naturally across outputs
- Keep age range mostly 18–35 unless context requires otherwise
- Occasionally include LGBTQ+ presentation only when it feels natural and not performative

Do NOT:
- default to the same gender or race repeatedly
- reuse identical styling (same haircut, outfit type, or vibe)
- create subjects that feel like slight variations of the same person

---

#### EXPRESSION & EMOTIONAL SIGNAL (MANDATORY)

Each subject must display a **clear, readable emotional state** tied to the hook:
- confused
- frustrated
- shocked
- skeptical
- exposed
- thinking
- relieved

Do NOT repeat the same emotional expression across consecutive outputs.

---

#### POSE & COMPOSITION (MANDATORY ROTATION)

Each image must use a **different primary pose style**.

Rotate through:
- holding item toward camera
- pointing at mistake
- hands-up pause
- X-arms rejection
- centered shock
- side glance
- over-the-shoulder look
- comparing two objects
- empty-wallet reveal
- presenter-style explanation
- duo interaction

Do NOT reuse the same pose structure back-to-back.

---

#### FRAMING

- Subject should face camera or be slightly angled unless another angle improves clarity or hook strength
- Maintain strong visual focus on the subject

---

#### ANTI-REPETITION RULE (CRITICAL)

Across a batch of outputs:
- No identical combination of:
  (archetype + gender + race + pose + emotion + styling)

Each image must feel like a **completely different person in a different situation**, not a variation of the same template.

---

#### INTERNAL GENERATION RULE (MANDATORY)

Before generating each image, internally assign:
- archetype
- gender presentation
- race/ethnicity
- emotional state
- pose style
- styling (outfit / vibe)

Ensure this profile is **unique from previous outputs**.

### 5.2 COMPOSITION VARIETY (MANDATORY)

Each output must use a meaningfully different layout.

Rotate across patterns such as:
- left-focused subject, open space on right
- right-focused subject, open space on left
- centered close-up
- centered medium shot with text above or beside
- foreground subject with deep background scene
- over-the-shoulder screen view
- split-screen comparison
- layered depth: subject in front, interface or scene behind
- subject holding a physical object toward camera
- subject holding proof item at chest height with enlarged overlay beside it
- central face between two competing objects or prices
- two-person composition with one reacting and one demonstrating
- subject on one side, oversized zoomed-in crop panel on the other
- subject making an X / stop gesture beside a highlighted mistake
- hands-up “hold up / wait” pose with quote text filling the opposite side
- subject in front of blurred document with marked errors
- subject beside giant map with route line and circled destination
- subject in front of giant UI panel / dashboard / inbox wall
- subject with floating icons / logos / badges around a proof object
- wide scenic background with subject cutout large in foreground
- scenic composite with tiny secondary figure placed in the landscape
- bottom-heavy object spread with human above or behind it
- food / product lineup across the bottom third
- top-banner headline with visual action below
- side headline block with subject reaction opposite
- boxed social post / tweet / comment card on one side, face on the other
- warning-banner bottom strip with presenter above
- diagonal flow using arrows, path lines, or gaze direction
- circular magnifier / callout around one key detail
- before-vs-after panel with good/bad symbols
- cluttered-chaos montage vs clean-solution panel
- studio portrait with minimal background and giant type
- surveillance / faux-recording frame overlay
- multi-monitor / control-room environment
- festival / market / restaurant wide scene with people + props
- desk / workstation / creator-setup scene
- travel postcard / destination composite
- dark studio + neon accent text
- bright clean white-background explainer style
- grayscale background with one highlighted accent color
- portrait plus inset crop of document / app / receipt / text message

Do not repeat the same composition pattern.  
For high-volume use, prefer **structural variety**, not just color changes.

### 5.3 BACKGROUND = CONTEXT SYSTEM

The background must represent the **problem behavior**, not generic decoration.

Possible background systems:
- repeated actions
- inboxes, dashboards, notifications, app UI
- visual metaphors such as loops, clones, walls, barriers, overload
- before/after contrast
- platform-adjacent UI cues

Do not invent niche details that the inputs do not support.  Background systems may include: multi-monitor setups, restaurant tables, festive markets, blurred documents, maps with route lines, dashboards, inboxes, social post cards, scenic travel composites, zoomed-in crops, product spreads, and faux camera / recording overlays.

### 5.4 TEXT PLACEMENT STRATEGY

Do **not** default to top text placement.

Place text where it strengthens tension:
- beside the mistake or pain point
- in negative space
- between the subject and the source of conflict
- over a clean area with strong contrast

Text rules:
- keep text short and mobile-readable
- prefer a 2-part hierarchy when possible:
  - line 1 = pattern interrupt
  - line 2 = payoff / clarification
- use bold, high-contrast styling
- yellow highlight blocks are allowed
- red accents may be used for danger, mistakes, or urgency
- avoid cluttered text overlays

### 5.5 COLOR & STYLE ROTATION

Avoid making every output dark, gloomy, or visually identical.

Rotate across visual moods such as:
- bright modern
- warm lifestyle
- high contrast
- soft pastel disruption
- corporate clean vs chaotic overlays

Each output should feel distinct at a glance.

### 5.6 VISUAL TENSION MECHANICS

Each output must include **at least 2** of the following:
- arrows pointing to mistakes
- circles or highlights around weak elements
- checkmarks vs X symbols
- contrast between good and bad
- overload vs clarity
- facial expression aligned with the pain signal

### 5.7 NICHE-ADAPTIVE EXECUTION

Do **not** hardcode a single niche such as resumes.

You must:
- interpret the behavior being called out
- translate that behavior into a visual system
- adapt the scene to the niche implied by the inputs

Possible niches include:
- career
- money
- fitness
- dating
- productivity
- education
- creator growth
- other adjacent self-improvement or outcome-driven topics  ### 5.8 SCENE EXAMPLE LIBRARY (MANDATORY REFERENCE POOL)

Use the following as valid scene families the model can rotate through. These are examples to include in the prompt’s internal scene pool, not a fixed list. The model should also invent additional scene families beyond these.

**A. Physical Proof Reveal**
- Human holding a resume, document, receipt, certificate, bill, or printed proof toward camera
- Large logos, icons, symbols, or question marks layered over the paper
- Good for: jobs, tech, money, scams, applications, audits, credibility

**B. Shocked Host + Environment + Bottom Objects**
- Host reacting in foreground
- Relevant environment behind them (gaming setup, office, restaurant, studio, workspace)
- Products, food, tools, or outputs arranged across the bottom foreground
- Good for: reviews, comparisons, “I tried this,” experience-based hooks

**C. Price Comparison Face-Off**
- Human centered between two competing items
- Big price on left, big price on right, “VS” in center
- Good for: cheap vs expensive, value gaps, budget vs premium, SaaS tiers, tools, services

**D. Duo Lifestyle / Taste-Test / Experience Scene**
- Two humans in frame
- One or both interacting with food, products, gifts, or experience items
- Festive, travel, market, or lifestyle background
- Good for: travel, dating, food, events, seasonal content, challenge formats

**E. Map Explainer / Route / Destination Callout**
- Giant map background
- Dotted route, arrow, or travel path
- Circled destination or zoom target
- Optional symbolic overlay: mascot, creature, vehicle, warning icon, or mythic visual hook
- Good for: travel, geopolitics, migration, logistics, storytime, “how I got there”

**F. Problem-Solution Career Explainer**
- Big high-contrast text block
- Human on one side doing a thinking / concern / “listen closely” pose
- Simple icons like phone, checkmark, graph, inbox, decline line
- Good for: career advice, productivity, application fixes, “do this not that”

**G. AI / Tool Opportunity Panel**
- Human host in foreground
- Robot, software screen, dashboard, or futuristic panel in background/side panel
- Text block tied to money, leverage, automation, or growth
- Good for: AI tools, software, no-code, agency, productivity monetization

**H. “Avoid This” Document Teardown**
- Enlarged crop of resume, spreadsheet, form, email, or UI
- Arrow pointing at the mistake
- Human making an X, stop sign, or disapproval gesture
- Bold warning text strip
- Good for: tutorials, mistakes, audits, breakdowns, critiques

**I. “Hold Up” Reaction Frame**
- Tight studio shot
- Human with hands up, skeptical face, or intense pause expression
- Quote-style or reaction-style text filling the other half
- Good for: commentary, hot takes, writing critique, persuasion, callout content

**J. Chaos / Tabloid / Viral Shock Montage**
- Intentional sensory overload
- Duplicate subject, giant emojis, oversized icons, faux camera overlays, chaotic props
- Use for sensational “what is happening?” energy
- Keep it non-graphic and platform-safe
- Good for: reaction content, absurd stories, gossip-style framing, chaotic hooks

**K. Empty Wallet / Lack vs Dream Outcome**
- Human holding wallet, bill, empty hand, or proof of lack in foreground
- Aspirational destination / lifestyle / result scene behind
- Good for: money, travel, budgeting, side hustles, transformation hooks

**L. Blur-the-Mistake Background**
- Document or screen blurred in background
- Red X marks or error markers on top
- Human reacting in foreground
- Good for: resume mistakes, bad landing pages, broken copy, UI critique, ad review

**M. Social Proof / Quote Card + Face**
- Tweet, post, DM, review, or quote card on one side
- Human face large on the other side reacting to or amplifying the message
- Good for: authority, wake-up calls, opinions, market commentary, quote breakdowns

**N. Zoomed Crop + Presenter**
- Main asset visible in frame
- Separate zoom box or crop panel highlighting one critical detail
- Presenter points, reacts, or blocks the bad area
- Good for: resumes, copy, offers, ads, analytics, product pages, spreadsheets

**O. Bottom-Spread Product Table**
- Human above or behind a row of food/products/tools spread across bottom
- Good for: comparisons, “best tools,” haul-style videos, reviews, challenge formats

**P. Scenic Composite + Giant Headline**
- Large travel or lifestyle background
- Subject cutout foreground
- Giant headline in the top/right/top-center zone
- Good for: travel, freedom, lifestyle, finance, personal story, relocation

The model must treat these as **starter scene families** and generate additional ones using the same logic. 

